<br />12 of 15 people found the following review helpful:
<br />
<br />Lencioni scores another hit, May 9, 2004
<br />Reviewer: MANUEL J HERNANDEZ "askmanny" (Orlando, FL) - See al</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Death by setting! Not helpful at all</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>5</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-19</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The author attributed the usual failure of meetings primarily to two problems: lack of drama (say, how to raise the interest of participants in the first ten minutes etc) and lack of contextual structure. For the later, he suggested four types of meeting including daily check-in, weekly tactical, monthly strategic and quarterly off-site review as remedy. 
<br />
<br />If you believe the above prescriptions suit your situation, fine. Go for it. If not, as in my case in a highly political (intra and inter departmental), competitive (business wise) where your boss and your boss's boss just make use of every opportunity to squeeze you for short term performance to meet requirement of quarterly target (in my case weekly targets) and find a scapegoat, please give it a pass. 
<br />
<br />p.s. The second key actor of the fable: The once sole proprietor of the software company had been kind and generous enough to sell his company to a publicly listed company and distribute the stock options to "cheer up" his staff. How kind and rare he had been! Hope you and me can come across one sooner or later!</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Should be required reading</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-11</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I'll add my voice to the many positive reviews this book has received. Death by Meeting clearly lays out the principles for holding effective meetings. Lencioni skillfully articulates key principles that WILL make a difference. Be forewarned, though; people generally will fall back into old habits without some consistent coaching and reminders. But once the former habits are broken, you will wonder how you ever got by.</span>
                  
              
